root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2428</fr:anchor><fr:addr>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.3</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.3.xml</fr:route><fr:number>7.2.3</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7.2</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
    It is clear that, if <fr:tex>(K,F,W)</fr:tex> is <fr:tex>F</fr:tex>-splitable, then <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2"
href="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2.xml"
taxon="Condition"
number="7.2.2"></fr:ref> is satisfied for <fr:tex>r_0=\infty </fr:tex>.
    Conversely, it seems that if <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2"
href="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2.xml"
taxon="Condition"
number="7.2.2"></fr:ref> is satisfied for <fr:tex>r_0=\infty </fr:tex>, then everything is as if the functor <fr:tex>\operatorname {Gr}_F</fr:tex> were exact.
    For example, we will show that the <fr:tex>\operatorname {Gr}_F</fr:tex> of the spectral sequence <fr:tex>E(K,W)</fr:tex> can then be identified with the spectral sequence <fr:tex>E(\operatorname {Gr}_FK,W)</fr:tex>, and that the spectral sequence <fr:tex>E(K,F)</fr:tex> degenerates (<fr:tex>E_1=E_\infty </fr:tex>).
  </fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter><fr:contributions></fr:contributions><fr:context><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="true"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2427</fr:anchor><fr:addr>hodge-theory-iii-7.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.xml</fr:route><fr:title><fr:link
href="hodge-theory-iii-7.xml"
type="local"
addr="hodge-theory-iii-7"><fr:link
href="hodge-theory-iii.xml"
type="local"
addr="hodge-theory-iii">Hodge Theory III</fr:link> › Supplements to §1</fr:link> › Supplements to the two filtrations lemma</fr:title><fr:number>7.2</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
  In this section, we give a new proof of the two filtrations lemma (<fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.16"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.16.xml"
taxon="Theorem"
number="1.3.16"></fr:ref>) and some supplements.
</fr:p><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>961</fr:anchor><fr:addr>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.1</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.1.xml</fr:route><fr:number>7.2.1</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7.2</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
    Let <fr:tex>(K,F,W)</fr:tex> be a bounded below bifiltered complex with objects in an abelian category <fr:tex>\mathscr {A}</fr:tex>, with <fr:tex>F</fr:tex> assumed to be biregular.
  </fr:p><fr:p>
    We say that <fr:tex>(K,F,W)</fr:tex> is <fr:em><fr:tex>F</fr:tex>-splitable</fr:em> if the filtered complex <fr:tex>(K,W)</fr:tex> can be written as a sum of filtered complexes
    <fr:tex
display="block">       (K,W)       = \bigoplus _{n\in \mathbb {Z}} (K_n,W_n)     </fr:tex>
    with
    <fr:tex
display="block">       F^nK       = \bigoplus _{n'\geqslant  n} K_{n'}.     </fr:tex></fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:p>
  Let <fr:tex>r_0\geqslant 0</fr:tex> be an integer or <fr:tex>+\infty </fr:tex>.
  The following condition was considered in <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.16"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.16.xml"
taxon="Theorem"
number="1.3.16"></fr:ref> and <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.17"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.17.xml"
taxon="Corollary"
number="1.3.17"></fr:ref>:
</fr:p><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>962</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Condition</fr:taxon><fr:addr>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2.xml</fr:route><fr:number>7.2.2</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7.2</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
    For every non-negative integer <fr:tex>r&lt;r_0</fr:tex>, the differentials <fr:tex>d_r</fr:tex> of the graded complex <fr:tex>E_r(K,W)</fr:tex> are strictly compatible with the recurrent filtration defined by <fr:tex>F</fr:tex>.
  </fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>963</fr:anchor><fr:addr>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.3</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.3.xml</fr:route><fr:number>7.2.3</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7.2</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
    It is clear that, if <fr:tex>(K,F,W)</fr:tex> is <fr:tex>F</fr:tex>-splitable, then <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2"
href="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2.xml"
taxon="Condition"
number="7.2.2"></fr:ref> is satisfied for <fr:tex>r_0=\infty </fr:tex>.
    Conversely, it seems that if <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2"
href="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2.xml"
taxon="Condition"
number="7.2.2"></fr:ref> is satisfied for <fr:tex>r_0=\infty </fr:tex>, then everything is as if the functor <fr:tex>\operatorname {Gr}_F</fr:tex> were exact.
    For example, we will show that the <fr:tex>\operatorname {Gr}_F</fr:tex> of the spectral sequence <fr:tex>E(K,W)</fr:tex> can then be identified with the spectral sequence <fr:tex>E(\operatorname {Gr}_FK,W)</fr:tex>, and that the spectral sequence <fr:tex>E(K,F)</fr:tex> degenerates (<fr:tex>E_1=E_\infty </fr:tex>).
  </fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>964</fr:anchor><fr:addr>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.4</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.4.xml</fr:route><fr:number>7.2.4</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7.2</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
    We immediately deduce from the definition (<fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.8"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.8.xml"
number="1.3.8"></fr:ref>) that the first direct filtration of <fr:tex>E_r(K,W)</fr:tex> is the filtration <fr:tex>F_d</fr:tex> of <fr:tex>E_r(K,W)</fr:tex> by the images
    <fr:tex
display="block">       F_d^p(E_r(K,W))       = \operatorname {Im} \big (E_r(F^pK,W) \to  E_r(K,W)\big ).     </fr:tex>
    Dually, the second direct filtration (<fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.9"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.9.xml"
number="1.3.9"></fr:ref>) of <fr:tex>E_r(K,W)</fr:tex> is the filtration <fr:tex>F_{d^*}</fr:tex> of <fr:tex>E_r(K,W)</fr:tex> by the kernels
    <fr:tex
display="block">       F_{d^*}^p(E_r(K,W))       = \operatorname {Ker} \big (E_r(K,W) \to  E_r(K/F^pK,W)\big ).     </fr:tex>
    The recurrent filtration <fr:tex>F_{\mathrm {rec}}</fr:tex> of <fr:tex>E_r(K,W)</fr:tex> is intermediary between these two filtrations ((iii) of <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.13"
href="hodge-theory-ii-1.3.13.xml"
taxon="Proposition"
number="1.3.13"></fr:ref>).
  </fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="false"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>969</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Proposition</fr:taxon><fr:addr>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.5</fr:addr><fr:route>hodge-theory-iii-7.2.5.xml</fr:route><fr:number>7.2.5</fr:number><fr:parent>hodge-theory-iii-7.2</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>
    Suppose that <fr:tex>(K,F,W)</fr:tex> satisfies <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2"
href="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2.xml"
taxon="Condition"
number="7.2.2"></fr:ref> for some <fr:tex>r_0\geqslant 0</fr:tex>.
    Then

    
 <html:ol
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(i) &quot;">
        <fr:tex>(F^aK/F^bK,F,W)</fr:tex> also satisfies <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2"
href="hodge-theory-iii-7.2.2.xml"
taxon="Condition"
number="7.2.2"></fr:ref> for <fr:tex>r_0</fr:tex>.
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li
style="list-style-type: &quot;(ii) &quot;">
        For <fr:tex>r\leqslant  r_0</fr:tex>, the sequence
        <fr:tex
display="block">           0           \to  E_r(F^pK,W)           \to  E_r(K,W)           \to  E_r(K/F^pK,W)           \to  0         </fr:tex>
        is exact;
        for <fr:tex>r=r_0+1</fr:tex>, the sequence
        <fr:tex
display="block">           E_r(F^pK,W)           \to  E_r(K,W)           \to  E_r(K/F^pK,W)         </fr:tex>
        is exact.
        In particular, for <fr:tex>r\leqslant  r_0+1</fr:tex>, the two direct filtrations and the recurrent filtration of <fr:tex>E_r(K,W)</fr:tex> agree.
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
  
    
